A `for` loop does not work like that.

What you&#39;re trying to do is check all numbers from 1 to 100 and stop searching when you find one that matches all criteria.

There are several ways to do that, but I would pick this: Use a `for` loop to cycle over all numbers from 1 to 100. Check if all the conditions apply, and if they do, print out the number and leave the loop.

    for (int x = 1; x &lt;= 100; x++) {
      if ((x % 6 == 0) &amp;&amp; 
          (x % 7 == 0) &amp;&amp; 
          (x % 4 == 0) &amp;&amp; 
          ((x / 10) + (x % 10) == 6)) {
        System.out.println(&quot;BINGO: &quot; + x);
        break;
      }
    }

For some reason you treated the condition with the 4 as different from the others, but it is not (*can be divided by* = the remainder is zero).

If you wanted to combine the if within the for, you can do it, but it works the other way round: you are supposed to put the condition required *to proceed* to the next run of the loop. It becomes this:

    int x;
    for (x = 1; 
        (x &lt;= 100) &amp;&amp;
        (x % 6 == 0) &amp;&amp; 
        (x % 7 == 0) &amp;&amp; 
        (x % 4 == 0) &amp;&amp; 
        ((x / 10) + (x % 10) == 6);
        x++) {
      // Does nothing here
    }
    System.out.println(&quot;BINGO: &quot; + x);

Notice that you need to declare `x` as an integer outside the `for` loop because you want to read it after you `break` out of the cycle.

The first version is definitely more readable (to humans).

